<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="130" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="129.[151,1437,1405,1898]" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1405,1430]" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The genus is characterized by its narrow slender appearance with rather long and thin legs and by coloration with distinct brown bands along the cross-veins of both fore and hind wings. On the tegmen, the media divides into MA and MP just before mid-length (in 
<taxonomicName authority="Ingrisch, 2018" authorityName="Ingrisch" authorityYear="2018" box="[732,842,1478,1501]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Australogryllacris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guttata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[732,842,1478,1501]" italics="true" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">A. guttata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[850,940,1477,1502]" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[850,940,1477,1502]" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Griffini, 1909)" authorityName="Griffini" authorityYear="1909" baseAuthorityName="Griffini" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[994,1272,1477,1502]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Australogryllacris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kirbyi">
<emphasis box="[994,1091,1477,1501]" italics="true" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">A. kirbyi</emphasis>
(Griffini, 1909)
</taxonomicName>
or near end of tegmen (in 
<taxonomicName authority="Brunner, 1888" authorityName="Brunner" authorityYear="1888" box="[281,649,1514,1538]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Gryllacris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="ornata" subSpecies="cyanea">
<emphasis box="[281,475,1514,1537]" italics="true" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">A. ornata cyanea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C." box="[484,649,1514,1538]" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" pagination="247 - 394" refId="ref184452" refString="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C. (1888) Monographie der Stenopelmatiden und Gryllacriden. Verhandlungen der Zoologisch- Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 38, 247 - 394, pls 5 - 9." type="journal article" year="1888">Brunner, 1888</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
), while CuA and CuP are both undivided. The genus was so far only known from females in two species and one subspecies. This is the first description of a male of this genus. The male abdominal structures are unique. The divided subgenital plate resembles the situation in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="2004" box="[1281,1429,1585,1609]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Furcilarnaca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1281,1429,1585,1609]" italics="true" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">Furcilarnaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karny" authorityYear="1937" box="[286,491,1621,1645]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Australogryllacris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[286,491,1621,1645]" italics="true" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">Australogryllacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is divided into three lobes nearly from base with the central lobe shorter and all lobes with simple obtuse tip; styli are absent while styli are present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="2004" box="[969,1117,1657,1681]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Furcilarnaca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[969,1117,1657,1681]" italics="true" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">Furcilarnaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The male ninth abdominal tergite of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karny" authorityYear="1937" box="[260,465,1693,1717]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Australogryllacris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[260,465,1693,1717]" italics="true" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">Australogryllacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is provided with a pair of small protuberances in apical area, while the tenth tergite is provided with a pair of bifold projections that have the dorsal end obtuse and the ventral end terminating into a sharp tooth, while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="2004" box="[392,540,1765,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Furcilarnaca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="129" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[392,540,1765,1789]" italics="true" pageId="129" pageNumber="130">Furcilarnaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are one pair of spines each on both ninth and tenth tergite. Characteristic for the genus are also the stout spines on internal ventral margin of the hind femora, especially the two last spines with the penultimate longer than the preceding spines and the last spine even longer and with widened base (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 44" captionStartId="130.[151,250,1916,1938]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,188,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@130.[149,1438,188,1904]" captionTargetPageId="130" captionText="FIGURE 44. Australogryllacris guttata sp. nov., holotype male: A, habitus dorsal view; B, face, C, apical area of hind femur with enlarged spines; D–I abdominal apex in lateral view (D), with cercus flipped aside (E), in apical view showing projections of tenth abdominal tergite (F, G), in ventral (H) and oblique ventral view (I) showing three-lobate subgenital plate and projections of tenth abdominal tergite from behind." pageId="129" pageNumber="130">Fig. 44C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
